@node Overview
@chapter Overview

The @samp{gdocs} package provides bidirectional synchronization between
org-mode files and Google Docs.  It lets you open, edit, create, and
push Google Docs entirely from within Emacs, using org-mode as the
native editing format.  The package handles OAuth 2.0 authentication,
format conversion, incremental diffing, and conflict resolution so that
your org files and their Google Docs counterparts stay in sync.

The package addresses three main workflows:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Publish org to Google Docs.}  Create a Google Doc from an existing
org file to share with collaborators.  The two files remain in sync:
edits to either propagate to the other.

@item
@strong{Read and edit shared Google Docs.}  Open a Google Doc shared by
someone else as an org-mode buffer in Emacs.  Edit without leaving
Emacs.

@item
@strong{Import existing Google Docs.}  Import old Google Docs into org
files.  The files remain synchronized, but you may later choose to
unlink or delete the Google Doc.
@end itemize

@menu
* Architecture::
* Dependencies::
* Quick start::
@end menu

@node Architecture
@section Architecture

The package is composed of several modules, each responsible for a
distinct layer of functionality:

@table @asis
@item @samp{gdocs.el}
Entry point, user commands, and the @code{gdocs-mode} minor
mode (@ref{Minor mode}).
@item @samp{gdocs-auth.el}
OAuth 2.0 flow, token management, and
multi-account support (@ref{Authentication}).
@item @samp{gdocs-api.el}
Asynchronous Google Docs and Google Drive API
client built on @samp{plz.el} (@ref{API client}).
@item @samp{gdocs-convert.el}
Bidirectional conversion between org-mode and
Google Docs JSON via an intermediate representation (IR)
(@ref{Format conversion}).
@item @samp{gdocs-diff.el}
Incremental diff engine that computes the minimal
set of API requests to synchronize changes (@ref{Diff engine}).
@item @samp{gdocs-sync.el}
Push/pull orchestration, shadow copy management,
and conflict detection (@ref{Sync engine}).
@item @samp{gdocs-merge.el}
Side-by-side conflict resolution interface
(@ref{Conflict resolution}).
@end table

All API operations are fully asynchronous via @samp{plz.el} so that Emacs
never blocks during network requests.

@node Dependencies
@section Dependencies

The package requires Emacs 29.1 or later and depends on the following
external packages:

@itemize
@item
@samp{plz} (0.7+) for asynchronous HTTP requests.
@item
@samp{dash} (2.19+) for list manipulation utilities.
@item
@samp{s} (1.13+) for string manipulation utilities.
@item
@samp{org} (9.6+), which is built into Emacs.
@end itemize

@node Quick start
@section Quick start

@enumerate
@item
Obtain OAuth credentials from Google Cloud Console
(@ref{Obtaining credentials}).

@item
Configure your credentials in Emacs:

@lisp
(setq gdocs-accounts
      '(("personal" . ((client-id . "YOUR-CLIENT-ID")
                       (client-secret . "YOUR-CLIENT-SECRET")))))
@end lisp

@item
Authenticate: @samp{M-x gdocs-authenticate}.

@item
Open an existing Google Doc: @samp{M-x gdocs-open}.

@item
Or create a new Google Doc from an org file: @samp{M-x gdocs-create}.
@end enumerate

Once a buffer is linked, the @code{gdocs-mode} minor mode activates
automatically.  Changes are pushed to Google Docs on every save (when
@code{gdocs-auto-push-on-save} is non-nil), and you can pull remote changes
at any time with @samp{M-x gdocs-pull}.

