@node Opening and creating documents
@section Opening and creating documents

@findex gdocs-open
@findex gdocs-create
The command @code{gdocs-open} fetches a Google Doc and opens it as an
org-mode buffer.  It prompts for a document ID or a full Google Docs
URL (e.g., @samp{https://docs.google.com/document/d/DOCUMENT-ID/edit}).  If
multiple accounts are configured in @code{gdocs-accounts}
(@ref{Account configuration}), it prompts you to select one.  The document is
converted from Google Docs JSON to org-mode format via the intermediate
representation (@ref{Format conversion}), saved to @code{gdocs-directory}
(@ref{File storage}) with a sanitized filename, and displayed in a buffer
with @code{gdocs-mode} active.

The command @code{gdocs-create} does the reverse: it creates a new Google
Doc from the current org buffer's content.  The title defaults to the
buffer's @samp{#+TITLE} keyword, falling back to the buffer name.  After
creating the document, the buffer is linked to it and @code{gdocs-mode} is
activated.  Subsequent saves push changes to the newly created Doc.

Both commands are autoloaded, so they are available without explicitly
loading the package.

@node Pushing and pulling
@section Pushing and pulling

@findex gdocs-push
@findex gdocs-pull
The command @code{gdocs-push} pushes local changes to the linked Google Doc.
If a shadow copy exists (i.e., the buffer has been synced at least once
in the current session), the push is incremental: only the differences
between the current buffer and the shadow are sent as Google Docs API
@code{batchUpdate} requests (@ref{Diff engine}).  If no shadow exists (for
example, after restarting Emacs), the push performs a full document
replacement.

When @code{gdocs-auto-push-on-save} is non-nil, @code{gdocs-push} is called
automatically after every save.  Pushes are serialized: if a push is
already in progress when another is triggered, the second push is
queued and executed after the first completes.

The command @code{gdocs-pull} fetches the latest version of the linked
Google Doc.  It first checks the document's revision ID via the Google
Drive API; if the revision matches the locally stored one, it reports
``Already up to date.''  If the revision differs, it fetches the full
document, converts it to org-mode format, and either replaces the
buffer content silently (when there are no local modifications) or
triggers the conflict resolution interface (@ref{Conflict resolution}).

@node Linking and unlinking
@section Linking and unlinking

@findex gdocs-link
@findex gdocs-unlink
The command @code{gdocs-link} links the current org buffer to an existing
Google Doc.  It prompts for a document ID or URL and, if needed, an
account.  Linking writes file-local variables (@samp{gdocs-document-id} and
@samp{gdocs-account}) to the end of the org file and triggers an initial
pull to establish the sync baseline.

The command @code{gdocs-unlink} removes the file-local variables and clears
all buffer-local sync state, turning the org file back into a
standalone document.  The file content is preserved; only the sync
metadata is removed.

@node Status and browser
@section Status and browser

@findex gdocs-status
@findex gdocs-open-in-browser
The command @code{gdocs-status} displays the current sync status in the echo
area.  It shows the linked document ID, account name, sync status
(synced, modified, pushing, conflict, or error), revision ID, and the
timestamp of the last sync.  This is useful for quickly verifying
whether the buffer is in sync without inspecting the modeline.

The command @code{gdocs-open-in-browser} opens the linked Google Doc in your
default web browser using @code{browse-url}.  It constructs the URL from
the stored document ID@.  This is convenient when you need to check
formatting, share the link with someone, or use Google Docs features
that are not yet supported in @samp{gdocs}.

@node Authentication
@section Authentication

@findex gdocs-authenticate
@findex gdocs-logout
The command @code{gdocs-authenticate} initiates the OAuth 2.0 flow for a
Google account (@ref{OAuth flow}).  If multiple accounts are configured, it
prompts you to select one.  The command opens your browser to Google's
consent screen, and a temporary local HTTP server receives the
authorization callback.  Upon successful authentication, tokens are
stored in @code{gdocs-token-directory} (@ref{Account configuration}).

The command @code{gdocs-logout} deletes the stored token file for an
account, effectively logging you out.  You will need to run
@code{gdocs-authenticate} again to re-authorize.

Both commands are autoloaded.

@node Conflict resolution (1)
@section Conflict resolution

@findex gdocs-merge-next-hunk
@findex gdocs-merge-previous-hunk
@findex gdocs-merge-accept-local
@findex gdocs-merge-accept-remote
@findex gdocs-merge-edit-hunk
@findex gdocs-merge-accept-all-local
@findex gdocs-merge-accept-all-remote
@findex gdocs-merge-finalize
@findex gdocs-merge-abort
When a pull detects that both local and remote changes exist, the
conflict resolution interface opens in a dedicated @samp{*gdocs-merge*}
buffer using @code{gdocs-merge-mode} (@ref{Merge mode}).  The following commands
are available in the merge buffer:

@itemize
@item
@code{gdocs-merge-next-hunk} (@samp{n}) moves to the next unresolved conflict
hunk.
@item
@code{gdocs-merge-previous-hunk} (@samp{p}) moves to the previous unresolved
hunk.
@item
@code{gdocs-merge-accept-local} (@samp{a}) accepts the local version of the
current hunk.
@item
@code{gdocs-merge-accept-remote} (@samp{b}) accepts the remote version of the
current hunk.
@item
@code{gdocs-merge-edit-hunk} (@samp{e}) opens a temporary org-mode buffer
pre-filled with the local text so you can edit the merged result
manually.  Press @samp{C-c C-c} in the edit buffer to accept.
@item
@code{gdocs-merge-accept-all-local} (@samp{A}) resolves all unresolved hunks
with the local version.
@item
@code{gdocs-merge-accept-all-remote} (@samp{B}) resolves all unresolved hunks
with the remote version.
@item
@code{gdocs-merge-finalize} (@samp{C-c C-c}) finalizes the merge once all
hunks are resolved, applies the merged content to the original
buffer, and triggers a push.  It signals an error if any hunks remain
unresolved.
@item
@code{gdocs-merge-abort} (@samp{C-c C-k} or @samp{q}) aborts the merge after
confirmation, leaving the buffer unchanged.
@end itemize

