@node OAuth flow
@section OAuth flow

The OAuth 2.0 flow works as follows:

@enumerate
@item
The user runs @samp{M-x gdocs-authenticate}.
@item
A temporary local HTTP server starts on a random high port to
receive the authorization callback.
@item
The user's default browser opens to Google's OAuth consent screen.
@item
After the user grants consent, Google redirects to the local server
with an authorization code.
@item
The package exchanges the code for access and refresh tokens.
@item
Tokens are stored in @code{gdocs-token-directory} with 600 permissions.
@end enumerate

The package requests two OAuth scopes:

@itemize
@item
@samp{https://www.googleapis.com/auth/documents} for reading and writing
Google Docs.
@item
@samp{https://www.googleapis.com/auth/drive} for listing, browsing, and
creating files in Google Drive.
@end itemize

@node Token management
@section Token management

Access tokens are refreshed automatically before each API call when
they are expired or within 60 seconds of expiry.  The refresh uses the
stored refresh token and happens asynchronously, so Emacs is never
blocked.  Each token file also stores the @samp{client_id} and
@samp{client_secret} so that token refreshes work without re-reading
@code{gdocs-accounts}.

If no token file exists for an account (e.g., after running
@code{gdocs-logout}), the next API operation triggers a fresh OAuth flow.

@node Multi-account support
@section Multi-account support

Each entry in @code{gdocs-accounts} is an independent account with its own
OAuth credentials and token file.  Linked org files remember which
account they are associated with via the @samp{gdocs-account} file-local
variable.  When you open a linked file, the stored account is used
automatically.

You would configure custom OAuth credentials per account if you want to
avoid shared rate limits or if your organization requires its own OAuth
application.

@node API client
@chapter API client

@menu
* Error handling and retries::
* Progress indication::
@end menu

@node Error handling and retries
@section Error handling and retries

All API requests include automatic retry logic for transient errors.
When the server returns HTTP 429 (rate limited), 500 (internal server
error), or 503 (service unavailable), the request is retried with
exponential backoff up to three times.  If the response includes a
@samp{Retry-After} header, its value is used as the delay; otherwise, the
delay follows the pattern 1s, 2s, 4s, capped at 30 seconds.

Authentication failures (HTTP 401 or 403) produce a clear error message
directing you to run @code{gdocs-authenticate} to re-authorize.

@node Progress indication
@section Progress indication

While API requests are in flight, the global modeline displays
@samp{[GDocs: syncing...]} to indicate that a network operation is in
progress.  The indicator disappears when all pending requests complete.

